 text to be encrypted is replaced by a letter a fixed number of positions a=
way in the alphabet. For example, using a right letter shift of four, A wou=
ld be replaced by E, and the word <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-diction=
ary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"CIPHER" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dict=
ionary/CIPHER" data-type=3D"EB">CIPHER</a> would become GMTLIV. The techniq=
ue is named after <span id=3D"ref1332921"></span><a href=3D"https://www.bri=
tannica.com/biography/Julius-Caesar-Roman-ruler" class=3D"md-crosslink " da=
ta-show-preview=3D"true">Julius Caesar</a>, who used it in his letters. The=
 simplicity of the Caesar cipher makes it a popular source for recreational=
 cryptograms.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span=
></section>               <!--[H2]--><span class=3D"marker h2"></span><div =
