=3D"marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong>=
<span id=3D"ref1023945"></span>cryptography</strong>,  Practice of the enci=
phering and <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-te=
rm=3D"deciphering" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/decipherin=
g" data-type=3D"EB">deciphering</a> of messages in secret code in order to =
render them unintelligible to all but the intended receiver. Cryptography m=
ay also refer to the art of cryptanalysis, by which cryptographic codes are=
 broken. Collectively, the <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/sc=
ience" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">science<=
/a> of secure and secret communications, involving both cryptography and cr=
yptanalysis, is known as <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/crypto=
logy" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">cryptolog=
y</a>. The principles of cryptography are today applied to the encryption o=
f <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/technology/fax" class=3D"md-crossli=
nk " data-show-preview=3D"true">fax</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.=
com/technology/television-technology" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-pre=
view=3D"true">television</a>, and computer <a href=3D"https://www.britannic=
a.com/technology/computer-network" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previe=
w=3D"true">network</a> communications. In particular, the secure exchange o=
f computer data is of great importance to banking, government, and commerci=
al communications. <em>See also</em> <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/=
technology/data-encryption" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"tr=
ue">data encryption</a>.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inl=
ine"></span></section>


